# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sevastopol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sevastopol/1-000-000-000] In standard form, it is written as **1 × 109**.
[src:sevastopol/1-000-000-000] The metric prefix giga indicates 1,000,000,000 times the base unit.
[src:sevastopol/1-000-000-000] One billion years may be called an *eon* in astronomy or geology.
[src:sevastopol/1-000-000-000] Previously in British English (but not in American English), the word "billion" referred exclusively to a million millions (1,000,000,000,000).
[src:sevastopol/1-000-000-000] However, this is not common anymore, and the word has been used to mean one thousand million (1,000,000,000) for several decades.
[src:sevastopol/1-000-000-000] The term ***milliard*** could also be used to refer to 1,000,000,000; whereas "milliard" is rarely used in English, variations on this name often appear in other languages.
[src:sevastopol/1-000-000-000] In the Indian numbering system, it is known as 100 crore or 1 arab.
[src:sevastopol/1-000-000-000] It is a common metric used in macroeconomics when describing national economies.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Russian Empire formally annexed the Crimean Khanate on 19 April [O.S.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] 8 April] 1783, following a decade-long campaign of intervention in the Crimean Peninsula.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Russia aimed to control the Black Sea and end raids by Crimean slavers into its territory.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] To accomplish this, the Russians waged a series of wars against the Ottoman Empire and its Crimean vassal state, culminating in victory in the 1768–1774 Russo-Turkish War.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Treaty of Küçük Kaynarca, signed in 1774, granted the Crimean Khanate nominal independence from the Ottomans under Russian influence.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In subsequent years, Russia would intervene widely in Crimean affairs, provoking a series of revolts by the Crimean Tatars, while the Ottomans watched in ambivalence.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Crimea was finally annexed by Russia on 19 April 1783, after Russian imperial advisor Prince Grigory Potemkin encouraged Empress Catherine the Great to dissolve the khanate and formally claim its territory.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The annexation ended the centuries-long Crimean slave trade.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Under Russian administration, the former khanate was subjected to a long-term policy of de-Tatarisation.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Tatar property was confiscated, and Russians were encouraged to settle in the region, sparking waves of Tatar emigration.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Crimea came under control of the Mongol Golden Horde in the mid-13th century AD.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Crimean Khanate was established in 1441 when Tatar Khan Hacı Giray broke away from the Horde.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The khanate became an Ottoman protectorate from 1475, with the southern shore of the Crimean Peninsula incorporated directly into the Ottoman Empire as a sanjak centred on the city of Kaffa (modern Feodosia).
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] This area was reorganised as Kaffa Eyalet in 1582.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Crimeans conducted frequent raids into neighbouring territories of Poland, Lithuania and Muscovy, capturing inhabitants and selling them as slaves to the Ottoman Empire in what is known as the "Crimean slave trade".
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Muscovite government paid regular tribute to the Khanate to ransom the captives.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Discontent with these raids eventually led to the Russo-Turkish War of 1735–1739, the first invasion of Crimea by the Russian Empire.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Russians ultimately withdrew, and the resulting Treaty of Niš ended the conflict.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Upon Catherine the Great's accession to the Russian throne, diplomat Mikhail Illarionovich Vorontsov provided information about the khanate, suggesting to her that Russian rule of Crimea, or removal of the Ottomans from it, was the only way to vacate the danger it posed.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] During the Russo-Turkish War of 1768–1774, Russia invaded Crimea.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In July 1771, the Russian army marched into Kaffa, and the Ottoman governor of Kaffa Eyalet was forced to flee to Constantinople.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Then leader of the Crimean Khanate, Selim Giray, surrendered to the invaders on 13 July.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Selim hoped that Russia would grant Crimea independence and maintain Giray rule.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Under pressure from the Russians, the Crimean elite elected Sahib Giray as their new khan.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In November 1771, a group of Crimean envoys led by *Kalgay* Şahin Giray visited Saint Petersburg to discuss the creation of an independent Crimean state under Russian protection.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In November 1772, representatives of Russia and Khan Sahib concluded the Treaty of Karasu Bazaar, which proclaimed the establishment of an independent state, including the former Kaffa Eyalet, and Russo-Crimean friendship.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] This could not come into effect without Ottoman recognition, however, which eventually came in 1774 with their defeat and the resulting Treaty of Küçük Kaynarca, wherein Russia and the Ottoman Empire agreed to Crimean independence.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Within two months of the signing of the treaty, however, the khanate government sent envoys to the Ottomans, requesting that they "destroy the conditions of independence".
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The envoys said that as Russian troops remained stationed in Crimea at Yeni-Kale and Kerch, the khanate could not be considered independent.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Nevertheless, the Ottomans ignored this request, not wishing to violate the agreement with Russia, which had granted it the right to garrison troops in these areas.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In the disorder that followed the Turkish defeat, Tatar leader Devlet Giray refused to accept the treaty at the time of its signing.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Having been fighting Russians in the Kuban during the war, he crossed the Kerch Strait to Crimea and seized Kaffa.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Devlet subsequently seized the Crimean throne, usurping Khan Sahib.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Despite his actions against the Russians, Russian empress Catherine the Great recognised Devlet as Khan.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] At the same time, however, she was grooming her favourite Şahin Giray, now resident at her court, for the role.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] As time went on, the rule of Devlet became increasingly untenable.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In July 1775, he sent a group of envoys to Constantinople to negotiate a re-entry of the Crimean Khanate into the Ottoman Empire.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] This action was in direct defiance of the Treaty of Küçük Kaynarca, which he asked the Ottomans to scrap.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Famed diplomat Ahmed Resmî Efendi, who had helped draft the treaty, refused to provide any assistance to the khanate, not wanting to start another disastrous war with Russia.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Catherine gave an order to invade Crimea in November 1776.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Her forces quickly gained control of Perekop, at the entrance to the peninsula.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In January 1777, Russian-supported Şahin Giray crossed into Crimea over the Kerch Strait, much as Devlet had done.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Devlet, aware of his impending defeat, abdicated and fled to Constantinople. Şahin was installed as a puppet Khan, infuriating the Muslim population of the peninsula.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] When he heard this news, Ottoman Sultan Abdul Hamid I noted "Şahin Giray is a tool.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The aim of the Russians is to take Crimea." Şahin, a member of the ruling House of Giray, attempted a series of reforms to "modernise" the khanate.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] These included attempts to centralise power in the hands of the Khan, establishing "autocratic" rule, much as in Russia.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Previously, power had been distributed between the leaders of different clans, called *beys*.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] He attempted to institute state taxation, a conscripted and centralised army, and to replace the traditional religion-based Ottoman legal system with civil law.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] These reforms, aimed at disrupting the old Ottoman order, were despised by the Crimean populace.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] At the behest of Catherine, Şahin allowed Russians to settle in the peninsula, further infuriating Crimeans.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] A group of these settlers had been sent to Yeni-Kale, which remained under Russian control following the installation of Şahin as Khan.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Local residents banded together to prevent the Russian settlement, rebelling against Şahin.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] He sent the new conscript army he had created to quash the rebellion, only to see his forces defect to the rebels.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Revolt spread across the peninsula, and rebel forces advanced on Şahin's palace in Bakhchysarai.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Amidst this rebellion, exiled Crimeans in Constantinople pressed the Ottoman government to act.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Bowing to pressure, the government sent a fleet to Crimea, ostensibly to preserve the Treaty of Küçük Kaynarca.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Russian forces arrived at Yeni-Kale in February 1778, crushing the revolt before the Ottoman fleet arrived.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] When the fleet arrived in March, it found that there were no rebels left to support.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] It fought a brief skirmish with the Russian navy off Akitar (modern Sevastopol), but was "forced" to flee. Şahin was reinstated as Khan.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Minor skirmishes between the Ottoman and Russian navies continued until October 1778, when the Ottoman fleet returned defeated to Constantinople.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Over the following years, Şahin continued to try and reform the khanate.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Support for his reform programme remained low, and it was seriously undermined by the decision of Catherine to resettle the Crimean Pontic Greeks on the northern shores of the Azov Sea, outside the khanate.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] That community, which was Christian, was an essential part of the Crimean merchant class, and had most readily supported Şahin's reforms.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] This resettlement caused significant damage to the Crimean economy, and further weakened the position of the Khan.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Recognising defeat in Crimea, the Ottoman Empire signed the Convention of Aynali Kavak in early 1779.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In the agreement, the Ottomans recognised Şahin as Khan of Crimea, promised no further intervention in Crimea, and conceded that Crimea was under Russian influence.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Crimeans could no longer expect support from the Ottomans. Şahin's reforms proceeded, gradually removing Tatars from positions of political influence.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] For a brief period, Crimea remained peaceful.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] A new rebellion, sparked by the continuing marginalisation of Tatars within the khanate government, started in 1781.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Various clan leaders and their forces came together in the Taman, across the Kerch Strait from Crimea.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In April 1782, a large portion of Şahin's army defected to the rebels, and joined them in the Taman.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Communication between rebel leaders, including two of Şahin's brothers, and the Crimean administrative elite was ongoing.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Religious (*ulama*) and legal (*kadı*) officials, important parts of the old Ottoman order, openly declared their antipathy for Şahin.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Rebel forces attacked Kaffa on 14 May [O.S.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] 3 May] 1782. Şahin's forces were swiftly defeated, and he was forced to escape to Russian-controlled Kerch.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Rebel leaders elected Şahin's brother Bahadır Giray as Khan, and sent a message to the Ottoman government seeking recognition.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] It was not long, however, before Catherine dispatched Prince Grigory Potemkin to restore Şahin to power.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] No significant opposition was fielded against the invading Russians, and many rebels fled back across the Kerch Strait.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] As such, the Khan was restored to his position in October 1782.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] By this time, however, he had lost the favour of both Crimeans and Catherine.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In a letter to a Russian advisor to Şahin, Catherine wrote "He must stop this shocking and cruel treatment and not give them [Crimeans] just cause for a new revolt".
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] As Russian troops entered the peninsula, work began to establish a Black Sea warm-water port for the Empire.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The city of Akitar (modern day Sevastopol) was chosen as the site of the port, which would go on to house the newly created Black Sea Fleet.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Uncertainty about the sustainability of the restoration of Şahin Giray, however, led to an increase of support for annexing Crimea, spearheaded by Potemkin.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In March 1783, Potemkin made a rhetorical push to encourage Catherine to annex Crimea.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Having just returned from Crimea, he told her that many Crimeans would "happily" submit to Russian rule.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Encouraged by this news, Catherine issued a formal proclamation of annexation on 19 April [O.S.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] 8 April] 1783; Şahin formally relinquished his claim to the khanate.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Tatars did not resist the annexation; after years of turmoil, the Crimeans lacked the resources and the will to continue fighting.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Many fled the peninsula, leaving for Anatolia.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Tens of thousands of these emigrants took up residence in Constantinople, where they formed an influential exile community, lobbying the Ottoman government to reclaim their Crimean homeland.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Crimean "independence" had been a puppet regime, and the Ottomans had played little role in the Crimean revolts.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Ottomans went on to recognise the loss of Crimea and other territories that had been held by the khanate in an agreement negotiated by Russian diplomat Yakov Bulgakov.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Known as the Treaty of Constantinople, it was signed on 28 December 1783 [O.S.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Crimea was formally incorporated into the Empire as "Taurida Oblast" during 1784, with Potemkin serving as its first governor.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Catherine visited her newly-claimed territories in an elaborate tour during 1787.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The annexation brought an end to the Crimean slave trade, and marked the beginning of Russian-imposed de-Tatarisation of Crimea.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] Following his appointment as governor of the region, Potemkin moved to expropriate Tatar land and assign it to Russian nobles, sparking another wave of Tatar emigration.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] In 1787, Potemkin even urged of the need to curb the Tatar flight due to the negative economic impact it was having on the region, but this proved unfruitful.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] The Ottomans would attempt to reclaim Crimea in the Russo-Turkish War of 1787–1792, but were defeated and forced to again acknowledge Russian rule in the Treaty of Jassy.
[src:sevastopol/1783-russian-annexation-of-crimea] This spurred a mass exodus of Tatars from Crimea; an estimate by Arsenii Markevich suggests that the Tatar population declined from approximately 300,000 at the time of the annexation to 170,000–180,000 in the aftermath of the 1792 treaty.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] In 1954, the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union transferred the Crimean Oblast from the Russian SFSR to the Ukrainian SSR.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Amidst the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991, the Ukrainian SSR seceded from the Soviet Union and Ukraine continued to exercise sovereignty over the territory as the Autonomous Republic of Crimea.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Russia recognised Crimea as being a part of Ukraine for over two decades, having signed the Belovezha Accords in 1991 as well as the Budapest Memorandum in 1994 to guarantee Ukraine's territorial integrity.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] But in 2014, it broke these guarantees and reverted its position when Crimea was annexed by Russia after coming under Russian military occupation.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Prior to being incorporated into the Russian Empire, the Crimean Peninsula was independent under the Crimean Khanate.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] The Muslim Turkic Crimean Tatars were under the influence of the Ottoman Empire, while also bordering the Russian Empire.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] In 1774, following the Russo-Turkish War of 1768–74, the Russian and Ottoman empires agreed to refrain from interfering with the Crimean Khanate through the Treaty of Küçük Kaynarca.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] In 1783, following the increasing decline of the Ottoman Empire, the Russian Empire annexed the Crimean Khanate.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Crimea was transferred between various internal administrations within Russia.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] It was governed by 14 administrations during its time in the Russian Empire and the Russian SFSR, up to its transfer to the Ukrainian SSR in 1954.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Throughout its time in the Soviet Union, Crimea underwent a population change.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Because of alleged collaboration with the Germans by Crimean Tatars during World War II, all Crimean Tatars were deported by the Soviet regime and the peninsula was resettled with other peoples, mainly Russians and Ukrainians.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Modern experts say that the deportation was part of the Soviet plan to gain access to the Dardanelles and acquire territory in Turkey, where the Tatars had Turkic ethnic kin, or to remove minorities from the Soviet Union's border regions.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Nearly 8,000 Crimean Tatars died during the deportation, and tens of thousands perished subsequently due to the harsh exile conditions.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] The deportation resulted in the abandonment of 80,000 households and 150,000 hectares (360,000 acres) of land.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] The autonomous republic without its titled nationality was downgraded to an oblast within the Russian SFSR on 30 June 1945.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] On 19 February 1954, the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union issued a decree transferring the Crimean Oblast from the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic to the Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] According to the Soviet Constitution (article 18), the borders of a republic within the Soviet Union could not be re-drawn without the agreement of the republic in question.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] The transfer was approved by the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] The constitutional change (articles 22 and 23) to accommodate the transfer was made several days after the decree issued by the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] The decree was first announced, on the front page of *Pravda*, on 27 February 1954.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Consequently, amendments were made to the republican constitutions of Russia and Ukraine.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Sevastopol became a closed city due to its importance as the port of the Soviet Black Sea Fleet and was attached to the Crimean Oblast only in 1978.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] The transfer of the Crimean oblast to Ukraine has been described as a "symbolic gesture", marking the 300th anniversary of the 1654 Treaty of Pereyaslav, called the "Reunification of Ukraine with Russia" in the Soviet Union.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] It was also attributed to Communist Party first secretary Nikita Khrushchev, although the person who signed the document was Chairman Kliment Voroshilov, the Soviet Union's *de jure* head of state.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Kramer believed that the transfer also aimed to greatly increase the number of ethnic Russians in the Ukrainian SSR which itself was going through problems integrating previous Polish territory due to organized Ukrainian nationalist resistance.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] He was ethnically Russian, but he really felt great affinity with Ukraine." Sergei Khrushchev, Khrushchev's son, claimed that the decision was due to the building of a hydro-electric dam on the Dnieper river and the consequent desire for all the administration to be under one body.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Since Sevastopol in Crimea was the site of the Black Sea Fleet, a quintessential element of Soviet and then of Russian foreign policy, the transfer had the intended effect of binding Ukraine inexorably to Russia, "Eternally Together", as a poster commemorating the event proclaimed.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Other reasons given were the integration of the economies of Ukraine and Crimea and the idea that Crimea was a natural extension of the Ukrainian steppes.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] There was also a desire to repopulate parts of Crimea with Slavic peoples, mainly Russians and Ukrainians, after the peninsula was subject to large-scale deportations of Crimean Tatars to Central Asia by the Soviet regime in 1944.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] The transfer increased the ethnic Russian population of Ukraine by almost a million people.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Prominent Russian politicians such as Alexander Rutskoy considered the transfer to be controversial.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] In January 1992, following Ukrainian independence, the Supreme Soviet of Russia questioned the constitutionality of the transfer, accusing Nikita Khrushchev of treason against the Russian people and said that the transfer was illegitimate.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] Alexander Rutskoy, the former Vice President of Russia, said that this was a "harebrained scheme", and that those who signed the document must have been suffering from sunstroke or hangovers.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] In 1994, a Russian nationalist administration under Yuriy Meshkov took over in Crimea with the promise to return Crimea to Russia, although these plans were later shelved.
[src:sevastopol/1954-transfer-of-crimea] In a 1997 treaty between the Russian Federation and Ukraine, Russia recognized Ukraine's borders, and accepted Ukraine's sovereignty over Crimea.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Montreal was awarded the rights to the 1976 Games at the 69th IOC Session in Amsterdam on May 12, 1970, over the bids of Moscow and Los Angeles.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] It is the only Summer Olympic Games to be held in Canada.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Toronto hosted the 1976 Summer Paralympics the same year as the Montreal Olympics, also the only Summer Paralympics to be held in Canada.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Calgary and Vancouver later hosted the Winter Olympic Games in 1988 and 2010, respectively.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] This was the first of two consecutive Olympic games held in North America, followed by the 1980 Winter Olympics in Lake Placid.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union won the most gold and overall medals, with the Eastern Bloc having seven countries in the top 10 of the medal table.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The vote occurred at the 69th IOC Session in Amsterdam, Netherlands on May 12, 1970.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] While Los Angeles and Moscow were viewed as the favourites, given that they represented the world's two main powers, many of the smaller and neutral countries supported Montreal as an underdog and as a relatively neutral site for the Games.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Los Angeles was eliminated after the first round, and Montreal won over Moscow in the second round.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Moscow and Los Angeles would go on to host the next two Summer Games, 1980 and 1984 Summer Olympics, respectively, which were also marked by political boycotts (for instance, the U.S.-led boycott of the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979).
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] One blank vote was cast in the second and final round.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The Soviet state media accused the IOC of political corruption following the vote, accusing them of facilitating the Soviet Union's loss.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Toronto had made its third attempt for the Olympics, as did Hamilton.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Still, they failed to win the support of the Canadian Olympic Committee, which selected Montreal instead.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Another candidate was the Italian city of Florence, which announced that it would withdraw from contention two months before the vote.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Robert Bourassa, then the Premier of Quebec, asked Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau to advise Canada's monarch Elizabeth II to attend the opening of the games.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] However, Bourassa later became unsettled about how unpopular the move might be with sovereigntists in the province, annoying Trudeau, who had already made arrangements.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] René Lévesque, the leader of the Parti Québécois at the time, sent his own letter to Buckingham Palace, asking the Queen to refuse her prime minister's request, but she did not oblige Lévesque as he was out of his jurisdiction in offering advice to the Sovereign.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] In 1976, Trudeau, succumbing to pressure from the People's Republic of China, issued an order barring Taiwan from participating as China in the 1976 Montreal Olympics, although it was technically a matter for the IOC.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] His action strained relations with the United States – from President Ford to future President Carter and the press.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Trudeau's action was widely condemned as having brought shame on Canada by succumbing to political pressure to keep the Taiwanese delegation from competing under its name.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The mascot was a beaver named Amik, whose name was chosen after a national competition.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The *Oxford Olympics Study* estimates the outturn cost of the Montreal 1976 Summer Olympics at US$6.1 billion in 2015 dollars and cost overrun at 720% in real terms.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] *Indirect* capital costs are not included, such as those for road, rail, or airport infrastructure, or for hotel upgrades or other business investment incurred in preparation for the Games but not directly related to staging the Games.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The cost overrun for Montreal 1976 is the highest cost overrun on record for any Olympics.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The cost and cost overrun for Montreal 1976 compares with costs of US$4.6 billion and a cost overrun of 51% for Rio de Janeiro in 2016 and $15 billion and 76% for London in 2012.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The average cost for the Summer Games from 1960 to 2016 was $5.2 billion in 2015 dollars, and the average cost overrun was 176%.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] French architect Roger Taillibert, who designed the Olympic stadium, recounted in his 2000 book *Notre Cher Stade Olympique* that he and Mayor Drapeau tried hard to buy off Desjardins, even taking him to a lunch at the exclusive Ritz-Carlton hotel in a vain attempt to end the "delays".
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] He suggests that Quebec Premier Robert Bourassa ultimately made a secret deal to buy off Desjardins, which allowed work to proceed.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Taillibert wrote in *Notre Cher Stade Olympique* "If the Olympic Games took place, it was thanks to Dede Desjardins.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] What irony!" The delays and scandals caused Quebec premier Robert Bourassa to take over the preparations of the games in November 1975.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The Vélodrome de Montréal, which was scheduled for opening in 1974, was finally completed in June 1976, a month before the opening ceremony.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony of the 1976 Summer Olympic Games was held at the incomplete Olympic Stadium in Montreal, Quebec on Saturday afternoon, July 17, 1976, in front of an audience of some 73,000 in the stadium and an estimated half billion watching on television.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Following an air show by the Canadian Forces Air Command's Snowbirds aerobatic flight demonstration squadron in the sunny skies above the stadium, the ceremony officially began at 3:00 pm with a trumpet fanfare and the arrival of Elizabeth II, as Queen of Canada.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The Queen entered the Royal Box with her consort, Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh, and her son, Prince Andrew.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] (Her daughter, Princess Anne, was competing as a member of Great Britain's equestrian team.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The parade of athletes began moments later with the arrival of the Greek team, and concluded with the entrance of the Canadian team.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] All other teams entered the stadium according to French alphabetical order (as the host city's main language).
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The ceremony was marked by the adorning of Israel's flag with a black mourning ribbon, in memory of the eleven athletes and coaches killed by Palestinian terrorists at the previous Summer Olympic Games in Munich four years earlier.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Although most would eventually boycott the Games in the days to follow, a number of African delegations did march in the parade.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Much of the music performed for the parade was arranged by Victor Vogel and was inspired by late Quebecois composer André Mathieu.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Immediately following the parade, a troupe of 80 female dancers dressed in white (representing the 80th anniversary of the revival of the Olympic Games) performed a brief dance in the outline of the Olympic rings.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Following that came the official speeches, first by Roger Rousseau, head of the Montreal Olympic organizing committee, and Lord Killanin.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Her Majesty was then invited to proclaim the Games open, which she did, first in French, then in English.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Accompanied by the Olympic Hymn, the Olympic flag was carried into the stadium and hoisted at the west end of the stadium.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The flag was carried by eight men and hoisted by four women, representing the ten provinces and two territories (at the time) of Canada.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] As the flag was hoisted, an all-male choir performed an a cappella version of the Olympic Hymn.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Once the flag was hosted, a troupe of Bavarian dancers representing Munich, host of the previous Summer Olympics, entered the stadium with the Antwerp flag.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Following a brief dance, that flag was then passed from the Mayor of Munich to the IOC President and then to the Mayor of Montreal.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Next came a presentation of traditional Québécois folk dancers.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The two troupes merged in dance together to the strains of "Vive le Compagnie" and exited the stadium with the Antwerp Flag, which would be displayed at Montreal City Hall until the opening of the 1980 Summer Olympics in Moscow.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Three cannons were then fired, as the 80-member troupe of female dancers unfolded special crates that released doves and ribbons in the five Olympic colours.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Another trumpet fanfare announced the arrival of the Olympic Flame.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The torch was carried by 15-year-olds Stéphane Préfontaine and Sandra Henderson, chosen as representatives of the unity within Canada's linguistic heritage.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] This would also be the first time two people would light the Olympic flame.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The duo would make a lap of the stadium and then climbed a staircase on a special dais at the centre of the stadium to set the Olympic flame alight in a temporary white aluminum cauldron.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The flame was later transported to a more permanent cauldron just outside the running track to burn throughout the duration of the Games.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] A choir then performed the Olympic Cantata as onlookers admired the Olympic flame.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The "Youth of Canada" took to the track to perform a colourful choreographed segment with flags, ribbons and a variety of rhythmic gymnast performers.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The flag bearers of each team then circled around the speaker's dais as Pierre St-Jean recited the Athletes' Oath and Maurice Forget recited the Judges' Oath, in English and in French, with right hands over their hearts and Canadian flags clutched in their left.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Finally, a choral performance of "O Canada" in both French and English marked the close of the opening ceremony, as the announcers concluded with a declaration of the Games motto: 'Vive les Jeux de Montreal!
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The Montreal ceremony would be the last of its kind in Summer Games, as future Olympic ceremonies, beginning with the new Olympic Charter were reinforced before the 1980 Summer Olympics, would become more focused on the host country's culture.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Because of the Munich massacre, security at these games was visible.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The extensive security measures included the requirement for all workers to hold a valid accreditation.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Surveillance of acoustics was installed in the Olympic Village where athletes were accommodated.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Furthermore, a systematic installation of closed-circuit television (CCTV) was attempted for the first time in the history of the Olympic games.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] There was a desire by the IOC's program commission to reduce the number of competitors and a number of recommendations were put to the IOC's executive board on February 23, 1973, which were all accepted.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Rowing was the only sport where the number of competitors was increased, and women were admitted for the first time in Olympic history.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Four nations made their first Summer Olympic appearance in Montreal: Andorra (which had its overall Olympic debut a few months before in Innsbruck Winter Olympics), Antigua and Barbuda (as *Antigua*), Cayman Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Numbers in parentheses indicate the number of athletes from each nation that competed at the Games.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1976 Games.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Canada placed 27th with only 11 medals in total, none of them being gold.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Canada remains the only host nation of a Summer Olympics to fail to win at least one gold medal.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] It also did not win any gold medals at the 1988 Winter Olympics in Calgary.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] However, Canada went on to win the most gold medals at the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The Games were dominated by the Soviet Bloc, with the USSR and its satellites occupying seven out of top ten places in the medal standings.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Twenty-nine countries boycotted the Games due to the refusal of the IOC to ban New Zealand, after the New Zealand national rugby union team had toured South Africa earlier in 1976.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The boycott was led by Congolese official Jean-Claude Ganga.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Some of the boycotting nations (including Morocco, Cameroon and Egypt) had already participated, however, and withdrew after the first few days.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Senegal and Ivory Coast were the only African countries that competed throughout the duration of the Games.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Elsewhere, Afghanistan, Albania, Burma, Iraq, Guyana, Sri Lanka and Syria also opted to join the Congolese-led boycott.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] South Africa had been banned from the Olympics since 1964 due to its apartheid policies.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Other countries, such as El Salvador and Zaire, did not participate in Montreal for purely economic reasons.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] An unrelated boycott of the Montreal Games was the main issue between the Republic of China (ROC) and the People's Republic of China (PRC).
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The ROC team withdrew from the games when Canada's Liberal government under Pierre Trudeau told it that the name "Republic of China" was not permissible at the Games because Canada had officially recognized the PRC in 1970.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Canada attempted a compromise by allowing the ROC the continued use of its national flag and anthem in the Montreal Olympic activities; the ROC refused.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] In 1979 the IOC established in the Nagoya Resolution that the PRC agreed to participate in IOC activities if the Republic of China was referred to as "Chinese Taipei".
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Another boycott would occur before the ROC would accept the provisions of the 1979 resolution.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Researchers from Germany in 2013 reported that West Germany had a state-sponsored doping program, and speculated it was in response to doping in East Germany which had existed for decades.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] ABC Sports paid US$25-million for television broadcast rights in the United States, and produced 76.5 hours of coverage.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] CBC Sports budgeted less than CAD$2-million and produced 169 hours of coverage, compared to 14 hours of programming at the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The network expanded its coverage in 1976, when convinced there would be increased media interest from Canadians.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] When the network was criticized for spending taxpayer dollars, executive producer Bob Moir toured the country to explain the project and boasted that, "the biggest team in Montreal will be the CBC team...
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] It will be bigger than the Canadian Olympic team".
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] CBC Sports had 245 people on its crew, and aired from 9 am until 11 pm daily, taking breaks only for newscasts.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Ted Reynolds and Lloyd Robertson co-hosted coverage of the opening ceremonies.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] In 1976, CBC Sports began its practice of talking live with athletes immediately after events, and built a studio for the interviews.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] CBC broadcasters were given information kits on the athletes, prepared by Jack Sullivan, the former sports editor of The Canadian Press.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The legacy of the Montreal Olympics is complex.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Many citizens regard the Olympiad as a financial disaster for the city as it faced debts for 30 years after the Games had finished.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The retractable roof of the Olympic Stadium never properly worked and on several occasions has torn, prompting the stadium to be closed for extended periods of time for repairs.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The failure of the Montreal Expos baseball club is largely blamed on the failure of the Olympic Stadium to transition into an effective and popular venue for the club – given the massive capacity of the stadium, it often looked unimpressive even with regular crowds in excess of 20,000 spectators.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The Quebec provincial government took over construction when it became evident in 1975 that work had fallen far behind schedule.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Work was still ongoing just weeks before the opening date, and the tower was not built.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Mayor Jean Drapeau had confidently predicted in 1970 that "the Olympics can no more have a deficit than a man can have a baby", but the debt racked up to a billion dollars that the Quebec government mandated the city pay in full.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] This would prompt cartoonist Aislin to draw a pregnant Drapeau on the telephone saying, "Allo, Morgentaler?" in reference to a Montreal abortion provider.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The Olympic Stadium was designed by French architect Roger Taillibert.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] It is often nicknamed "The Big O" as a reference to both its name and to the doughnut-shape of the permanent component of the stadium's roof, though "The Big Owe" has been used to reference the astronomical cost of the stadium and the 1976 Olympics as a whole.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] It has never had an effective retractable roof, and the tower (called the Montreal Tower) was completed only eleven years after the Olympic Games, in 1987.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] In December 2006 the stadium's costs were finally paid in full.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The total expenditure (including repairs, renovations, construction, interest, and inflation) amounted to C$1.61 billion.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Today the stadium lacks a permanent tenant, as the Montreal Alouettes and Montreal Expos have moved, though it does host some individual games of the Alouettes as well as CF Montréal (formerly the Montreal Impact).
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] One of the streets surrounding the Olympic Stadium was renamed to honour Pierre de Coubertin, the founder of the Olympics.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The boycott by African nations over the inclusion of New Zealand, whose rugby team had played in South Africa that year, was a contributing factor in the massive protests and civil disobedience that occurred during the 1981 Springbok Tour of New Zealand.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Official sporting contacts between South Africa and New Zealand did not occur again until after the fall of apartheid.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] Australia's failure to win a gold medal led the country to create the Australian Institute of Sport.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] In 2016, the 40th anniversary celebrations were held.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] In conjunction with the celebrations, the 2016 Quebec Games were held.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The games were the subject of *Games of the XXI Olympiad (Jeux de la XXIe olympiade)*, a 1977 documentary film by Jean Beaudin, Marcel Carrière, Georges Dufaux and Jean-Claude Labrecque.
[src:sevastopol/1976-summer-olympics] The 1976 games were also an inspiration for Australian band Black Cab's double album of 2014 entitled *Games of the XXI Olympiad*.
[src:sevastopol/1992-constitution-of-crimea] After a referendum on 20 January 1991, Crimea regained its status as an Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic.
[src:sevastopol/1992-constitution-of-crimea] As this was months before the Declaration of Independence of Ukraine on 24 August 1991 — by December 1991 internationally recognized — Crimea was at the time part of the Ukrainian SSR which was one of the constituent republics of the Soviet Union.
[src:sevastopol/1992-constitution-of-crimea] On 26 February 1992, the Crimean parliament changed the name of the region from the Crimean ASSR into the Republic of Crimea and the Ukrainian government with the objective of allowing them more self-governance.
[src:sevastopol/1992-constitution-of-crimea] On 5 May 1992, parliament declared Crimea independent and adopted a constitution, which was yet to be approved by a referendum to be held 2 August 1992.
[src:sevastopol/1992-constitution-of-crimea] On 6 May 1992, the same parliament inserted a new sentence into this constitution stating that Crimea was part of Ukraine.
[src:sevastopol/1992-constitution-of-crimea] The Ukrainian parliament convened on May 15, annulled the Crimean declaration of independence and gave the Crimean parliament one week to cancel the referendum.
[src:sevastopol/1992-constitution-of-crimea] In June 1992, the parties reached a compromise, Crimea would be designated the status of "Autonomous Republic" and granted special economic status, contingent on Crimea's amendment of its constitution including proclaiming the peninsula an autonomous integral part of Ukraine.
[src:sevastopol/1992-constitution-of-crimea] The revised Constitution of Crimea was adopted on September 25, 1992.
[src:sevastopol/1992-constitution-of-crimea] In May 1994, the Crimean parliament voted to restore the May 1992 Constitution although this was abandoned by September of that year.
[src:sevastopol/1992-constitution-of-crimea] In March 2014, following its capture by Russian soldiers, the Crimean Parliament proposed a referendum to whether Crimea should apply to join Russia as a federal subject or restore the 1992 Crimean constitution - and so remain within Ukraine with considerable autonomy.
[src:sevastopol/1992-constitution-of-crimea] According to the official results, the vote was to join Russia.
[src:sevastopol/1992-constitution-of-crimea] The referendum was later declared invalid by the United Nations General Assembly Resolution 68/262.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] The constitution establishes the republic's status and authority within Ukraine.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] It granted Crimea the right to draft a budget and manage its own property.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] During the 2014 Crimean crisis, a disputed referendum led to the repeal of the constitution by the Crimean government, as part of the process by which the territory was annexed by Russia as the Republic of Crimea.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] The Ukrainian government has not recognized this annexation, and still recognizes the constitution as active.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] As this was months before August's Declaration of Independence of Ukraine Crimea was at the time part of the Ukrainian SSR which was one of the constituent republics of the Soviet Union.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] In 26 February 1992, the Crimean parliament changed the name of the region from the Crimean ASSR into the Republic of Crimea and the Ukrainian government with the objective of allowing them more self-governance.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] On 5 May 1992, parliament declared Crimea independent, which was yet to be approved by a referendum to be held 2 August 1992.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] In May 1994, the Crimean parliament voted to restore the May 1992 Constitution.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] In September 1994, President of Crimea Yuriy Meshkov and parliament decided to write a new constitution.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] On 17 March 1995, the Verkhovna Rada abolished the May 1992 Constitution and the post of President of Crimea.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] From June until September 1995, Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma governed Crimea under a direct presidential administration decree.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] In October 1995, the Crimean parliament adopted a new Constitution which was not recognized by the Ukrainian national authorities until April 1996 when significant amendments were suggested.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] A fifth draft law of the October 1995 constitution was ratified on 21 October 1998 at the second session of the Crimean Verkhovna Rada (parliament).
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] The Verkhovna Rada confirmed this constitution on 23 December 1998.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] (Article 135 of the Ukrainian Constitution provides that the Crimean Constitution must be approved by the Ukrainian parliament.) It came into effect on 12 January 1999.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] During the annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation, the Crimean authority repealed the 1998 Crimean Constitution after the 2014 Crimean status referendum.
[src:sevastopol/1998-constitution-of-crimea] The Crimean parliament had no right of legislative initiative.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] A dispute over Tuzla Island in the Kerch Strait arose between Russia and Ukraine in 2003, sparked by unannounced Russian construction of a causeway from their side of the strait toward the island, which is Ukrainian territory.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Russians offered various reasons for building the causeway, but Ukraine saw it as a threat to their territorial integrity.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The dispute raised fears of an armed confrontation, but a settlement was negotiated.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Tuzla Island is a sandy island off the coast of the Crimean Peninsula.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Formerly a spit connected by land to the Kuban region of Russia, it was disconnected from it by a heavy storm in 1925.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] In 1941, the island was transferred to the Crimean Autonomous Socialist Soviet Republic, which was part of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] It became the Crimean Oblast in 1945, and the oblast was transferred to the Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic in 1954.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Tuzla Island came under the control of the briefly independent Republic of Crimea before joining with Ukraine when the Crimean parliament joined Ukraine in 1995.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Russia recognized Ukrainian sovereignty over Crimea in the Russian–Ukrainian Friendship Treaty of 1997, but the status of Tuzla Island was not settled and remained a sore spot in Russia–Ukraine relations.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The governor of Krasnodar Krai, Alexksandr Tkachyov, said in 2003, "...
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] I think that this is land that was bathed in Cossack blood, and therefore it is our sacred land," claiming the island as part of Russia.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Tkachyov later met with the deputy speaker of the Russian duma, Vladimir Zhirinovsky, who then claimed that the majority of the Duma backed the Russian claim over Tuzla Island.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Controlling the island would give either country much control over the shipping to the Sea of Azov and for that reason it was seen as a priority for the Ukrainian government.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] In 2003, the island was home to a dozen families of Ukrainian fishermen, and two vacation resorts.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] On September 9, 2003, Russians began construction of a causeway from the Taman Peninsula in Krasnodar Krai towards Tuzla Island.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The work began rapidly, without notice, with up to 180 dump truck loads of earth an hour being dropped into the sea.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] There were several stories regarding what entity in Russia authorised the construction.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] One had it that a local self-government body of the Kuban Cossacks authorised construction to reduce saltwater flow to Taman Bay, to thus improve conditions for certain species of fish.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] According to this story, many Kuban Cossack activists were among the construction workers.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Kyiv newspaper *Zerkalo Nedeli* suggested that it was supported by local Crimean and Russian businessmen and Ukrainian Communist politician Leonid Hrach to convince Ukraine and Russia to build a bridge over Kerch Strait to facilitate trade.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Officials in Krasnodar Krai said they were just rebuilding the pre-1925 land connection, to protect their coastal area from flooding.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The central government in Moscow likewise said it was to prevent erosion of the coast.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Romanian-American political analyst Vladimir Socor claimed that the construction was by Russia's Ministry of Emergency Situations.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] He said that Russian president Vladimir Putin personally ordered and oversaw the construction, with the purpose of connecting Russia to Tuzla Island, making it part of the Russian mainland.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] He said that Russia was attempting to seize control of the strait's main shipping channel from Ukraine.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The Ukrainian government responded by deploying border troops of the Simferopol Detachment on the island.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] On October 21, 2003, the Russian tugboat *Truzhenik* crossed the border to photograph and film border posts and defences on the island and was detained by the Border Service of Ukraine.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The Ukrainians released the tugboat after armed Russian coastal guard boats arrived.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] On October 23, 2003, the Verkhovna Rada issued a resolution "to eliminate a threat to the territorial integrity of Ukraine that appeared as a result of dam construction by the Russian Federation in the strait of Kerch".
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] A provisional special parliamentary commission was created to investigate the case more thoroughly.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] On October 30–31, 2003, talks started between Ukraine and Russia in order to deflate the crisis.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] President Kuchma ended the confrontation through an undeclared compromise, accepting terms disadvantageous to Ukraine, in return for Russian authorities halting construction of the causeway and accepting the continuation of Ukrainian sovereignty over the strait's navigable channel.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The incident damaged Leonid Kuchma's reputation domestically, as he was accused of attempting to control Ukrainian media reporting on the event.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] Disputes about right of passage were resolved by a 2003 bilateral agreement on cooperation in the use of the Sea of Azov and the Kerch Strait, which made these water bodies shared internal waters of both countries.
[src:sevastopol/2003-tuzla-island-conflict] The island came under full Russian control following the 2014 Russian annexation of Crimea, and they built the Kerch Strait Bridge partly on it.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Sevastopol, along with the rest of Crimea, is internationally recognised as part of Ukraine, and under the Ukrainian legal framework, it is administratively one of two cities with special status (the other being Kyiv).
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] However, it has been occupied by Russia since 27 February 2014, before Russia annexed Crimea on 18 March 2014 and gave it the status of a federal city of Russia.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Both Ukraine and Russia consider the city administratively separate from the Autonomous Republic of Crimea and the Republic of Crimea, respectively.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The city's population has an ethnic Russian majority and a substantial minority of Ukrainians and Crimean Tatars.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Sevastopol's unique naval and maritime features have been the basis for a robust economy.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The city enjoys mild winters and moderately warm summers, characteristics that help make it a popular seaside resort and tourist destination, mainly for visitors from the former Soviet republics.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The city is also an important centre for marine biology research.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In particular, the military has studied and trained dolphins in the city for military use since the 1960s.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The name of Sevastopolis was originally chosen following the same etymological trend as other cities in the Crimean peninsula; it was intended to express its ancient Greek origins.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The city was probably named after Empress ("Augusta") Catherine II of the Russian Empire who founded Sevastopol in 1783.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] She visited the city in 1787, accompanied by Joseph II, the Emperor of Austria, and other foreign dignitaries.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In the west of the city, there are well-preserved ruins of the ancient Greek port city of Chersonesos, founded in the 5th century BC by settlers from Heraclea Pontica.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] This name means "peninsula", reflecting its immediate location.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] It is not related to the ancient Greek name for the Crimean Peninsula as a whole: *Chersonēsos Taurikē* ("the Taurian Peninsula").
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In the 6th century BC, a Greek colony was established in the area of the modern-day city.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The Greek city of Chersonesus existed for almost two thousand years, first as an independent democracy and later as part of the Bosporan Kingdom.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In the 13th and 14th centuries, it was sacked by the Golden Horde several times and was finally totally abandoned.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The modern day city of Sevastopol has no connection to the ancient and medieval Greek city other than geographical location, but the ruins are a popular tourist attraction located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Sevastopol was founded in June 1783 as a base for a naval squadron under the name Akhtiar (*White Cliff*), by Rear Admiral Thomas MacKenzie ("Foma Fomich Makenzi"), a native Scot in Russian service; soon after, the Russian Empire annexed the Crimean Khanate.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Five years earlier, Alexander Suvorov had ordered that earthworks be erected along the harbour and Russian troops be placed there.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The Crimean Tatar version of this name is now written *Aqyar*.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In February 1784, Catherine the Great ordered Grigory Potyomkin to build a fortress there and call it Sevastopol.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The realisation of the initial building plans fell to Captain Fyodor Ushakov who in 1788 was named commander of the port and of the Black Sea squadron.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The city was established on the western shore of Southern Bay which branches away from the bigger Sevastopol Bay.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The ruins of ancient Chersonesus were situated to the west.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The newly built settlement became an important naval base and later a commercial seaport.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In 1797, under an edict issued by Emperor Paul I, the military stronghold was again renamed Akhtiar.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Finally, on 29 April (10 May), 1826, the Senate returned the city's name to Sevastopol.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In 1803 to 1864 along with Mykolaiv the city was part of Nikolayev–Sevastopol Military Governorate.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The town had 3,000 inhabitants by the 1840s.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] From 1853 to 1856, the Crimean peninsula's strategic position in controlling the Black Sea caused it to be the site of the principal engagements of the Crimean War, where Russia lost to a French-led alliance.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] After a minor skirmish at Köstence (now Constanța), the allied commanders decided to attack Sevastopol as Russia's main naval base in the Black Sea.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] After extended preparations, allied forces landed on the peninsula in September 1854 and marched to a point south of Sevastopol after winning the Battle of the Alma on 20 September.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The Russians counterattacked on 25 October in what became the Battle of Balaclava and were repulsed, but the British Army's forces were seriously depleted as a result.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] A second Russian counterattack, at Inkerman in November, ended in a stalemate as well.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The front settled into the siege of Sevastopol, involving brutal conditions for troops on both sides.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Sevastopol finally fell after eleven months, after the French had assaulted Fort Malakoff.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Isolated and facing a bleak prospect of invasion by the West if the war continued, Russia sued for peace in March 1856.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] France and Britain welcomed the development, owing to the conflict's domestic unpopularity.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The Treaty of Paris, signed on 30 March 1856, ended the war and forbade Russia from basing warships in the Black Sea.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] This hampered the Russians during the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–78 and in the aftermath of that conflict, Russia moved to reconstitute its naval strength and fortifications in the Black Sea.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] During World War II, Sevastopol withstood intensive bombardment by the Germans in 1941–42, supported by their Italian and Romanian allies during the Battle of Sevastopol.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] German forces used railway artillery—including history's largest-ever calibre railway artillery piece in battle, the 80-cm calibre *Schwerer Gustav*—and specialised mobile heavy mortars to destroy Sevastopol's extremely heavy fortifications, such as the Maxim Gorky Fortresses.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] After fierce fighting, which lasted for 250 days, the fortress city finally fell to Axis forces in July 1942.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] It was liberated by the Red Army on 9 May 1944 and was awarded the Hero City title a year later.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] During the Soviet era, Sevastopol became a so-called "closed city".
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] This meant that any non-residents had to apply to the authorities for a temporary permit to visit the city.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] On 29 October 1948, the Presidium of the Supreme Council of the Russian SFSR issued an *ukaz* (order) which confirmed the special status of the city.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Soviet academic publications since 1954, including the *Great Soviet Encyclopedia*, indicated that Sevastopol, Crimean Oblast was part of the Ukrainian SSR.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In 1954, under Nikita Khrushchev, both Sevastopol and the remainder of the Crimean peninsula were administratively transferred from being territories within the Russian SFSR to being territories administered by the Ukrainian SSR.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Administratively, Sevastopol was a municipality excluded from the adjacent Crimean Oblast.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The territory of the municipality was 863.5 km2 and it was further subdivided into four raions (districts).
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Besides the City of Sevastopol proper, it also included two towns—Balaklava (having had no status until 1957), Inkerman, urban-type settlement Kacha, and 29 villages.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] For the 1955 Ukrainian parliamentary elections on 27 February, Sevastopol was split into two electoral districts, Stalinsky and Korabelny (initially requested three Stalinsky, Korabelny, and Nakhimovsky).
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Eventually, Sevastopol received two people's deputies of the Ukrainian SSR elected to the Verkhovna Rada, A.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In 1957, the town of Balaklava was incorporated into Sevastopol.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Following Ukraine's declaration of independence from the USSR in 1991, Sevastopol became the principal base of the Ukrainian navy.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] As the key naval base of the former Soviet Black Sea Fleet, it was a source of tensions for Russia–Ukraine relations until a set-term lease agreement was signed in 1997.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] On 10 July 1993, the Russian parliament passed a resolution declaring Sevastopol to be "a federal Russian city".
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] At the time, many supporters of President Boris Yeltsin had ceased taking part in the parliament's work.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] On 20 July 1993, the United Nations Security Council denounced the decision of the Russian parliament.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] According to Anatoliy Zlenko, it was the first time that the council had to review and qualify actions of a legislative body.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] On 14 April 1993, the Presidium of the Crimean Parliament called for the creation of the presidential post of the Crimean Republic.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] A week later, the Russian deputy, Valentin Agafonov, said that Russia was ready to supervise a referendum on Crimean independence and include the republic as a separate entity in the CIS.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] On 28 July 1993, one of the leaders of the Russian Society of Crimea, Viktor Prusakov, said that his organisation was ready for an armed mutiny and the establishment of Russian administration of Sevastopol.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In September, the commander of the joint Russian-Ukrainian Black Sea Fleet, Eduard Baltin, accused Ukraine of converting some of his fleet and conducting an armed assault on his personnel and threatened to take countermeasures placing the fleet on alert.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] (In June 1992, the Russian president Yeltsin and the Ukrainian president Leonid Kravchuk had agreed to divide the former Soviet Black Sea Fleet between Russia and Ukraine.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The Moscow mayor Yury Luzhkov claimed the city, and in December 1996, the Russian Federation Council officially endorsed the claim, threatening negotiations.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In response, Ukraine proposed a "special partnership" with NATO in January 1997.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In May 1997, Russia and Ukraine signed the Russian–Ukrainian Friendship Treaty, ruling out Moscow's territorial claims to Ukraine.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] This was followed by the Partition Treaty on the Status and Conditions of the Black Sea Fleet on 28 May 1997.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] A separate agreement established the terms of a long-term lease of land, facilities, and resources in Sevastopol and the Crimea by Russia.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Russia kept its naval base, with around 15,000 troops stationed in Sevastopol.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The ex-Soviet Black Sea Fleet and its facilities were divided between Russia's Black Sea Fleet and the Ukrainian Naval Forces.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The two navies co-used some of the city's harbours and piers, while others were demilitarised or used by either country.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Sevastopol remained the location of the Russian Black Sea Fleet headquarters, and the Ukrainian Naval Forces Headquarters were also located in the city.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] A judicial row periodically continued over the naval hydrographic infrastructure both in Sevastopol and on the Crimean coast (especially lighthouses historically maintained by the Soviet and Russian Navy and also used for civil navigation support).
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] As in the rest of Crimea, Russian remained the predominant language of the city, although following the independence of Ukraine there were some attempts at Ukrainisation, with very little success.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Russian society in general and even some outspoken government representatives never accepted the loss of Sevastopol and tended to regard it as temporarily separated from Russia.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] On 27 April 2010, Russia and Ukraine ratified the Russian Ukrainian Naval Base for Gas treaty, which extended the Russian Navy's lease of the Crimean facilities for 25 years after 2017 (through 2042) with the option to prolong the lease in five-year extensions.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The ratification process in the Ukrainian parliament encountered stiff opposition and even resulted in a brawl in the parliament chamber.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Eventually, the treaty was ratified by a 52% majority vote—236 of 450.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The Russian Duma ratified the treaty by a 98% majority.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] On 23 February 2014, a pro-Russian rally took place in Nakhimov Square declaring allegiance to Russia and protesting against the new government in Kyiv following the overthrow of the president, Viktor Yanukovych.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] On 27 February, pro-Russian militia, including Russian troops, seized control of government buildings in Crimea, and by 28 February, controlled other strategic locations such as the military airport in Sevastopol.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] On 16 March 2014, an internationally unrecognised referendum was held in Sevastopol with official results claiming an 89.51% turnout and 95.6% of voters choosing to join Russia.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Ukraine and almost all other countries of the United Nations General Assembly consider the referendum illegal and illegitimate.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] On 18 March, Russia annexed Crimea, incorporating the Republic of Crimea and federal city of Sevastopol as federal subjects of Russia.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] However, the annexation remains internationally unrecognised, with most countries recognising Sevastopol as a city with special status within Ukraine.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] While Russia has taken *de facto* control of Sevastopol and Crimea, the international community considers the area as part of Ukraine.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] , on the southwestern coast of Sevastopol.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The city of Sevastopol is located at the southwestern tip of the Crimean peninsula in a headland known as Heracles peninsula on a coast of the Black Sea.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The city is designated a special city-region of Ukraine which besides the city itself includes several of its outlying settlements.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The city itself is concentrated mostly in the western portion of the region and around the long Bay of Sevastopol.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] This bay is a ria, a river canyon drowned by Holocene sea-level rise, and the outlet of Chorna River.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Away in a remote location southeast of Sevastopol is located the former city of Balaklava (since 1957 incorporated within Sevastopol), the bay of which in the Soviet era served as a main port for the Soviet diesel-powered submarines.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The coastline of the region is mostly rocky, in a series of smaller bays, a great number of which are located within the Bay of Sevastopol.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The biggest of them are Southern Bay (within the Bay of Sevastopol), Archer Bay, a gulf complex that consists of Deergrass Bay, the Bay of Cossack, Salty Bay, and many others.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] There are over thirty bays in the immediate region.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Three rivers flow through the region: the Belbek, Chorna, and Kacha.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] All three mountain chains of the Crimean mountains are represented in Sevastopol, the southern chain by the Balaklava Highlands, the inner chain by the Mekenziev Mountains, and the outer chain by the Kara-Tau Upland (Black Mountain).
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Sevastopol has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen: *Cfa*).
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Due to the summer mean straddling 22 °C (72 °F) it borders on a four-season oceanic climate, with cold winters and warm summers.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The average yearly temperature is 15–16 °C (59–61 °F) during the day and around 9 °C (48 °F) at night.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In the coldest months, January and February, the average temperature is 5–6 °C (41–43 °F) during the day and around 1 °C (34 °F) at night.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In the warmest months, July and August, the average temperature is around 26 °C (79 °F) during the day and around 19 °C (66 °F) at night.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Generally, the summer/holiday season lasts 5 months, from around mid-May and into September, with the temperature often reaching 20 °C (68 °F) or more in the first half of October.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The average annual temperature of the sea is 14.2 °C (58 °F), ranging from 7 °C (45 °F) in February to 24 °C (75 °F) in August.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] From June to September, the average sea temperature is greater than 20 °C (68 °F).
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In the second half of May and the first half of October; the average sea temperature is about 17 °C (63 °F).
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The average rainfall is about 400 millimetres (16 in) per year.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] There are about 2,345 hours of sunshine duration per year.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Since 18 March 2014, when Russia annexed Crimea, including Sevastopol, the *de facto* government and politics of Sevastopol has been that of a federal city of Russia.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The head of the executive branch in the city is the Governor of Sevastopol.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] According to the city charter, amended on 29 November 2016, the governor is elected in a direct election for a term of five years and no more than two consecutive terms.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The current governor is Mikhail Razvozhayev.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] During the annexation of Ukrainian Crimea by Russia, the pro-Russian Sevastopol City Council threw its support behind Russian citizen Alexei Chaly as a "people's mayor" and said it would not recognise orders from Kyiv.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] After Russia annexed Crimea, the Legislative Assembly of Sevastopol replaced the City Council.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Within the Russian municipal framework, the territory of the federal city of Sevastopol is divided into nine municipal okrugs and the town of Inkerman.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] While individual municipal divisions are contained within the borders of the administrative districts, they are not otherwise related to the administrative districts.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Sevastopol elects one Deputy to the Russian State Duma.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The current Deputy, Tatyana Lobach of United Russia, a former Deputy Chairwoman of the Legislative Assembly of Sevastopol, was elected at the 2021 Russian legislative elections.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] According to the Constitution of Ukraine, Sevastopol is administered as a City with special status.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Executive power in Sevastopol is exercised by the Sevastopol City State Administration, led by a chairman (also known as mayor) appointed by the Ukrainian president.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The Sevastopol City Council is the legislature of Sevastopol.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Apart from navy-related civil facilities, Sevastopol hosts some other notable industries.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] An example is Stroitel, a major plastic manufacturer.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Sevastopol Shipyard comprises three facilities that together repair, modernise, and re-equip Russian Naval ships and submarines.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The Sevastopol International Airport is used as a military aerodrome at the moment and being reconstructed to be used by international airlines.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Sevastopol maintains a large port facility in the Bay of Sevastopol and in smaller bays around the Heracles peninsula.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The port handles traffic from passengers (local transportation and cruise), cargo, and commercial fishing.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The port infrastructure is fully integrated with the city of Sevastopol and the naval bases of the Black Sea Fleet.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Due to its military history, most streets in the city are named after Russian and Soviet military heroes.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] There are hundreds of monuments and plaques in various parts of Sevastopol commemorating its military past.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The population of Sevastopol is 509,992, consisting of 479,394 urban residents and 30,598 rural (January 2021), making it the most populous city of the Crimean Peninsula.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The city has retained an ethnic Russian majority throughout its history.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In 2015, Sevastopol had the largest decrease in life expectancy at birth among all regions of Russia.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In 2020, after beginning of the COVID-19 pandemic, Sevastopol became the only region of Russia where there was increase of life expectancy.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] In 2021, average life expectancy at birth in Sevastopol was 72.25 years (67.87 for males and 76.43 for females).
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] There are many historical buildings in the central and eastern parts of the city and Balaklava, some of which are architectural monuments.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] The Western districts have modern architecture.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] More recently, numerous skyscrapers have been built.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] Balaklava Bayfront Plaza (on hold), currently under construction, will be one of the tallest buildings in Ukraine, at 173 m (568 ft) with 43 floors.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] After the 2014 Russian annexation of Crimea the city's monument to Petro Konashevych-Sahaidachny was removed and handed over to Kharkiv.
[src:sevastopol/sevastopol] FC Sevastopol is a professional football club that plays in the Russian Second League Division B, the fourth tier of the Russian football system.
